*Certainty: 0.40.* Tryptophan‚ÜíNAD‚Āļ pathway is established biochemistry ‚ÄĒ tryptophan is converted through the kynurenine pathway to quinolinic acid, then to nicotinic acid mononucleotide (NaMN) ‚Üí NAD‚Āļ. IDO-driven tryptophan diversion (documented in ME/CFS) simultaneously depletes serotonin (tryptophan‚Üí5-HT pathway) AND NAD‚Āļ (tryptophan‚Üíkynurenine‚ÜíNAD‚Āļ pathway ‚ÄĒ the kynurenine diversion prevents both). Additionally, NAD‚Āļ is consumed by: (a) PARP (DNA repair enzyme) ‚ÄĒ activated by oxidative DNA damage ‚Üí depletes NAD‚Āļ; (b) CD38 (NAD‚Āļ glycohydrolase on immune cells) ‚ÄĒ upregulated by inflammatory cytokines ‚Üí degrades NAD‚Āļ; (c) sirtuins (NAD‚Āļ-dependent deacetylases) ‚ÄĒ consume NAD‚Āļ for epigenetic regulation. The combination of reduced synthesis (tryptophan diversion) and increased consumption (PARP, CD38, sirtuins) ‚Üí severe NAD‚Āļ depletion ‚Üí NAD‚Āļ/NADH ratio collapse ‚Üí impaired mitochondrial Complex I (NADH‚ÜíNAD‚Āļ), impaired sirtuin activity (SIRT1, SIRT3), impaired PARP-mediated DNA repair, and impaired glycolysis (GAPDH requires NAD‚Āļ). NMN/NR supplementation has not been studied in ME/CFS controlled trials.

